[7] Emergency consideration
Date: Thu 23 Jun 2022
Source: ABC News [edited]
https://www.abc.net.au/news/2022-06-23/african-scientists-criticise-who-over-monkeypox-declaration/101179034


The World Health Organization (WHO) will soon decide whether to declare monkeypox a global health emergency, stirring criticism from leading African scientists who say it has been a crisis in their region for years. The deliberations and scrutiny of the WHO's response to the outbreak follow concerns over how the UN agency and governments worldwide handled COVID-19 in early 2020.

Monkeypox does not spread nearly as easily as SARS-CoV-2, the virus that causes COVID-19, and there are vaccines and treatments available unlike for the coronavirus when it emerged. But it has still raised alarm. The case count from the current outbreak outside of Africa has topped 3000 in more than 40 countries, according to a Reuters tally -- largely among men who have sex with men -- since it was 1st reported in May [2022].

The viral disease, which causes flu-like symptoms and skin lesions, is endemic in parts of Africa. The continent has registered just over 1500 suspected cases since the start of 2022, of which 66 have been fatal, according to official data.

"When a disease affects developing countries, it is not an emergency. It only becomes an emergency when developed countries are affected," said Emmanuel Nakoune, acting director of the Institut Pasteur in Bangui, the Central African Republic, who is running a trial of a monkeypox treatment. However, Professor Nakoune said if the WHO declared a "public health emergency of international concern" -- its highest level of alarm -- it would still be an important step. "If there is the political will to share equitably the means of response between developed and developing countries ... each country will be able to benefit," he said.

WHO has said it is working on a mechanism for sharing treatments and vaccines.

The emergency committee meeting considering the ruling includes experts from the most-affected regions, who have also consulted with scientists including Professor Nakoune. They will make a recommendation to WHO director-general Tedros Adhanom Ghebreyesus, who makes the ultimate decision over whether to call the emergency. The step mainly functions to sound the alarm, and can prompt further guidance from the organisation, as well as focus attention among member states.

Most experts agree monkeypox technically meets the criteria for the WHO definition of an emergency. It is a sudden and unusual event spreading internationally, and requires cross-country co-operation.

But the WHO is in a precarious position after COVID-19, according to Clare Wenham, a global health assistant professor at the London School of Economics. If WHO declared an emergency and countries did not act, it could undermine the agency's role in controlling global disease, she said. "They're damned if they do and damned if they don't," she said.

--
communicated by:
ProMED

[Because the monkeypox (MPX) cases that occur in several African countries are individual cases or small clusters that occur sporadically, they have garnered little international attention except when infected individuals travel from Africa to industrial countries and become ill there. If the WHO decision is made to deal with MPX in Africa, the challenge will be deciding what preventive measures to use. If vaccination is the main preventive method selected, deciding where, when and who to vaccinate will not be an easy one financially, logistically and socially. - Mod.TY]

******
[8] Local transmission
Date: Thu 23 June 2022
Source: Reuters [edited]
https://www.reuters.com/world/us/us-cdc-confirms-evidence-local-monkeypox-transmission-2022-06-23/


The US Centers for Disease Control and Prevention (CDC) said there was evidence of local transmission of monkeypox, in addition to reports of cases where people had traveled abroad. The cases are mainly occurring in men who have sex with men, but women are also getting infected, CDC staff member Dr Agam Rao said at a panel meeting on Thursday [23 Jun 2022].

Monkeypox, a viral infection that causes skin lesions, is endemic in certain parts of Africa. But the current outbreak has hit countries where the virus does not usually spread, sparking concern.

CDC said there had also been reports of transmission among family members and close contacts. "We also heard worldwide about close contacts like close household members who for example shared bedding, towels, have acquired infection," Rao said. "So it is not just through close intimate contact that this is being spread."

The lesions associated with the present outbreak are also smaller than those typical of classic monkeypox, according to the public health agency.

CDC last month [May 2022] published guidelines recommending the use of Bavarian Nordic's (BAVA.CO) Jynneos vaccine for laboratory personnel and other at-risk people, making another vaccine available in addition to Emergent BioSolutions' (EBS.N) ACAM2000.

Earlier on Thursday [23 Jun 2022], New York City opened a temporary clinic to administer the 2-dose Jynneos vaccine to eligible people who may have been exposed to monkeypox, including gay and bisexual men. While there have been cases of heart inflammation called myocarditis associated with ACAM2000, no such cases have been reported yet after the use of Jynneos, CDC said. There is a limited supply of Jynneos and the agency is considering how to best use the supplies, it said.

[byline: Amruta Khandekar]

